Interestingly, the kill procedure in Perl explicitely checks for non-numbers, which is unusual. Perl as a language would just cast undef to zero in a numeric context[1], and &#x27;kill $signal, 0&#x27; would go on killing every process in the process group.<p><pre><code>  $ perl -we &#x27;kill 9, undef&#x27;
  Can&#x27;t kill a non-numeric process ID at -e line 1.
</code></pre>
[1] unless you &quot;use warnings FATAL => &#x27;uninitialized&#x27;;&quot;
